But Sir, before you proceed any farther, give mee leave to tell you how groſſely you are miſtaken in what I ſaid; I ſaid not that you joyned with them on purpoſe to make your ſelves miſerable thereby, but that you through your folly took the onely courſe to bring your ſelves into that condition, if that ſome of you act and go on in the ſame way that ſome of us did before you; I remember a verſe much to this purpoſe;
It is no leſſe then a ſilent Invitation,
Although we ſcorn the ſin, to give the occaſion. If you will not bee convinced now that ſome of you were in an errour, and approve of what I have ſaid to be true, I will call the Army to be a Moderator betwixt us; were not ſome Yorkſhire men at Burford?
